<br>
1) Players take priority over pets, I don't think anyone can/will argue that fact, pets don't lose xp, their master doesn't, only cost a bit of mana to summon a new pet, no biggy. And in most groups, if your pet is taking damage, you are at cause. AoE can be avoided or largely mitigated by the mages putting on his resists gear (or in my case, simply being a resist freak to begin with), enrage damage is solely the responsability of the mage, a good mage will rarely have his pet hit on enrage.<br>
<br>
2) In groups where a pet is MT (and yes it's very doable in PoP, I often duo with slowers and if it's an enchanter i have no problem at all keeping my pet alive with my own heals versus slowed PoP mobs up to tier 3), the healer (clr,dru,shm) should and will heal the pet. <br>
<br>
3) Buffing pets like you buff players is worth it.<br>
<br>
4) In certain circumstances, a pet will have to tank an add or something like that, this is when point 3 becomes important and where healers should look at the direction of the pet. Personnally though I don't rely on group healer for those situation, sure I appreciate if they can land a hand, but maybe they are in the middle of CH or something like that and simply can't heal pet. Since if I put pet on an add I am aware of it, I go into healing mode. I can keep my pet alive pretty long without slow even against PoP mobs (planar renewal + transon renewal chain + pet mend + focused air pet), mana intensive, yes, but usualy long enough to buy time for the rest of the group to react to the add (slow it, heal pet, etc).<br>
<br>
5) All classes hate mages, because we are way sexier than they are.<br>
<br>
6) That was all there was to learn in this thread. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=75721">Woon</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://tde.e-slackers.net/">&lt;TDE&gt;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <br>
